{"title_page": "2019\u201320 Dundee F.C. season", "text_new": "The [[2019\u201320 in Scottish football|2019\u201320 season]] was [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee's]] first season back in the second flight of Scottish football since their relegation at the end of the [[2018\u201319 Scottish Premiership|2018\u201319]] season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/dundee-0-1-hamilton-dark-blues-relegated-as-accies-edge-closer-to-safety-1-4920932|title=Dundee 0-1 Hamilton: Dark Blues relegated as Accies edge closer to safety|last=Pattullo|first=Alan|date=4 May 2019|website=The Scotsman|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 May 2019}}</ref> {{Infobox football club season|club=[[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]]|season=[[2019\u201320 in Scottish football|2019\u201320]]|manager=[[James McPake]]|chairman=Tim Keyes|stadium=[[Dens Park]]|league=[[2019\u201320 Scottish Championship|Scottish Championship]]|league result=3rd place|cup1=[[2019\u201320 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]|cup1 result=Second Round|cup2=[[2019\u201320 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]]|cup2 result=Fourth Round|league topscorer=[[Kane Hemmings]] (10)|season topscorer=[[Kane Hemmings]] (10)|highest attendance=11,233 [[Dundee derby|vs]] [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], 8 November 2019 ([[2019\u201320 Scottish Championship|Cham.]])|lowest attendance=1,619 vs [[Elgin City F.C.|Elgin City]], 8 September 2019 ([[2019-20 Scottish Challenge Cup|CC]])|average attendance=5,277|pattern_la1=_dundeefc1920h|pattern_b1=_dundeefc1920h|pattern_ra1=_dundeefc1920h|pattern_sh1=_dundeefc1920h2|pattern_so1=_dundee1920h|leftarm1=|body1=|rightarm1=|shorts1=|socks1=010040|pattern_la2=_dundeefc1920a|pattern_b2=_dundeefc1920a|pattern_ra2=_dundeefc1920a|pattern_sh2=_dundeefc1920a|pattern_so2=|leftarm2=|body2=|rightarm2=|shorts2=|socks2=|image=Dundee1617badge.png|image_size=175px|pattern_la3=_dundeefc1920t|pattern_b3=_dundeefc1920t|pattern_ra3=_dundeefc1920t|prevseason=[[2018\u201319 Dundee F.C. season|2018\u201319]]|nextseason=[[2020\u201321 Dundee F.C. season|2020\u201321]]|cup3=[[2019\u201320 Scottish Challenge Cup|Challenge Cup]]|cup3 result=Third Round|socks3=010040|pattern_sh3=_dundeefc1920t}}Dundee also competed in the [[2019-20 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]], the [[2019\u201320 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]] and the [[Scottish Challenge Cup|Challenge Cup]].\n\nOn March 13 2020, the Scottish football season was suspended with immediate effect due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spfl.co.uk/news/coronavirus-joint-response-group-update-46618|title=Coronavirus \u2013 Joint Response Group Update|date=13 March 2020|publisher=SPFL|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> On April 15, a resolution by the [[Scottish Professional Football League|SPFL]] passed, cancelling the Championship season early and cancelling the play-offs.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://spfl.co.uk/news/spfl-resolution-approved-by-clubs-in-all-four-di|title=SPFL Resolution approved by clubs in all four divisions|last=|first=|date=15 April 2020|website=SPFL.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Season summary==\n\n===Pre-season===\nDundee hired former U18s and reserve manager [[James McPake]] as manager for the 2019\u201320 season, and also hired former [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] manager and current [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland national team]] assistant manager [[Jimmy Nicholl]] as assistant manager.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dundeefc.co.uk/news/james-and-jimmy-appointed-as-management-team/|title=James and Jimmy appointed as management team|last=|first=|date=31 May 2019|website=Dundee FC Official Website|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/48470814|title=Dundee: James McPake confirmed as club's new manager|last=|first=|date=31 May 2019|website=BBC|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 May 2019}}</ref> On 18 July, it was announced that [[Gordon Strachan]] would become Technical Director of the club, with a large focus of his role being in the development of the club's Youth Academy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dundeefc.co.uk/news/gordon-strachan-appointed-technical-director/|title=Gordon Strachan appointed Technical Director|last=|first=|date=18 July 2019|website=dundeefc.co.uk|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===July===\nTheir opening competitive games in the [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] gave reason both for optimism and concern. Coming out of their first match away to [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]], Dundee left with an impressive 0\u20133 victory behind them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/raith-vs-dundee/407298|title=Raith 0\u20133 Dundee|last=|first=|date=13 July 2019|website=Sky Sports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> However, this strong win was followed by two consecutive frustrating goalless draws against lower league opposition, though both results were masked somewhat through the Dees winning both penalty shootouts to gain extra points in both matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48994256|title=Cove Rangers v Dundee|last=|first=|date=17 July 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48994807|title=Dundee v Peterhead|last=|first=|date=20 July 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> Dundee closed out their League Cup group campaign with a 1\u20130 home win over fellow Championship side [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness CT]], cementing the side as group winners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48998412|title=Dundee 1\u20130 Inverness CT|last=|first=|date=28 July 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===August===\nThe league campaign got underway away to [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline]]. After a dismal first half display where the Pars went up by 2 and were unlucky to not score more, Dundee came out with a draw after [[Danny Johnson (footballer)|Danny Johnson]] netted two penalties and the side improved in the second half to leave with a point.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49122738|title=Dunfermline Athletic 2\u20132 Dundee|last=McLauchlin|first=Brian|date=2 August 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> Dundee followed up with a more impressive showing at Dens, defeating [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] 1\u20130 via an [[Andrew Nelson (footballer)|Andrew Nelson]] header.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49216203|title=Dundee 1\u20130 Ayr United|last=Spence|first=Jim|date=10 August 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> In their League Cup second round match, Dundee would provide tough opposition to [[Scottish Premiership|Premiership]] side [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] and would lead for the majority for the game, before the Dons netted a late equaliser and then a winner in extra time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49324403|title=Dundee 1\u20132 Aberdeen (AET)|last=McLauchlin|first=Brian|date=18 August 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> Upon returning to league action, Dundee would play out a 0\u20130 draw at home against Inverness,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49379023|title=Dundee 0\u20130 Inverness CT|last=Smith|first=Tyrone|date=24 August 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> before taking on rivals [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] in the first [[Dundee derby]] in 2 years, and the first league derby since the Dees relegated their rivals from the Premiership three years prior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36126882|title=Dundee 2\u20131 Dundee United|last=English|first=Tom|date=2 May 2016|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> In front of over 14,000 fans at [[Tannadice Park|Tannadice]], a bizarre and controversial game swung the way of the Terrors, who ran out 6\u20132 winners in what was a rough night for the Dark Blues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30600732|title=Dundee United 6\u20132 Dundee|last=Elgott|first=Jordan|date=30 August 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===September===\nAny hope of a quick bounce-back after the derby humiliation was lost when Dundee once again underperformed against lower league opposition and went out in embarrassing fashion at home to [[Elgin City F.C.|Elgin City]] in the [[Scottish Challenge Cup|Challenge Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/dundee-vs-elgin-city/420163|title=Dundee 1\u20132 Elgin City|last=|first=|date=8 September 2019|website=Sky Sports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> In their return to league action, Dundee mustered an important 2\u20131 home win against [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa]] to end their winless run,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49618118|title=Dundee 2\u20131 Alloa Athletic|last=Crawford|first=Kenny|date=14 September 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> but could not keep the momentum up and lost their next game on the road to [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49698676|title=Greenock Morton 1\u20130 Dundee|last=Crawford|first=Kenny|date=21 September 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> The away struggles continued for the Dee, as they had to settle for a point against [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] the following week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49764509|title=Queen of the South 1\u20131 Dundee|last=Elgott|first=Jordan|date=27 September 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===October===\nUpon their return to Dens, Dundee had a more confident and encouraging showing against [[Arbroath F.C.|Arbroath]], running out 2\u20130 winners with relative comfort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49861598|title=Dundee 2\u20130 Arbroath|last=|first=|date=5 October 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 October 2019}}</ref> The struggle to maintain a positive streak continued however, as a late collapse led to a defeat to [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50024542|title=Dundee 1\u20133 Partick Thistle|last=|first=|date=19 October 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 October 2019}}</ref> Under pressure to improve performance in a tight league, the Dee would win their first away league game of the season in a hard-fought contest against [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50092701|title=Ayr United 1\u20132 Dundee|last=|first=|date=25 October 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 October 2019}}</ref> and followed that up with their first consecutive league wins since May 2018 with a comfortable 0\u20133 away to [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50134336|title=Alloa Athletic 0\u20133 Dundee|last=Crawford|first=Kenny|date=29 October 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===November===\nDundee's positive momentum continued with their third consecutive victory, in a home game against [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50177711|title=Dundee 2\u20131 Greenock Morton|last=Crawford|first=Kenny|date=1 November 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 November 2019}}</ref> This was the first time in exactly 5 years since Dundee last won three league games in a row, as well as the first team they defeated not starting with 'A' in the league. This positive momentum did not carry into the [[Dundee derby]], as [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] battled their way to another victory over their rivals in a sold out [[Dens Park]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50258130|title=Dundee 0\u20132 Dundee United|last=Bienkowski|first=Stefan|date=8 November 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 November 2019}}</ref> After a two week break, Dundee turned in another unimpressive display, losing away to Inverness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50443292|title=Inverness CT 1\u20130 Dundee|last=Davies|first=Eilidh|date=23 November 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 November 2019}}</ref> The Dark Blues' woes continued the following week, and despite scoring a late equaliser, they immediately gave away a losing goal to Queen of the South.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50526734|title=Dundee 1\u20132 Queen of the South|last=Mann|first=Charlie|date=30 November 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===December===\nDundee managed to take a point from Arbroath at [[Gayfield Park]] to end their three-game losing streak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50611428|title=Arbroath 1\u20131 Dundee|last=Mann|first=Charlie|date=7 December 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 December 2019}}</ref> Desperate for an end to their winless run, Dundee put on a terrific first-half performance against on-form Dunfermline, making it 4\u20131 just after the second half began. Despite playing against 10 men for the majority of the second half, Dundee once again collapsed defensively, letting their opponents claw back. The Dee however managed to hang on and survive with a 4\u20133 victory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50696531|title=Dundee 4\u20133 Dunfermline Athletic|last=|first=|date=14 December 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 December 2019}}</ref> The positive momentum continued with an away clean sheet win against Partick Thistle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50791778|title=Partick Thistle 0\u20131 Dundee|last=|first=|date=21 December 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 December 2019}}</ref> Dundee closed out the year with a very respectable performance and draw away to league leaders and rivals [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], being the first team to take points off of them at [[Tannadice Park|Tannadice]], and moved up to third place for the new year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/50862390|title=Dundee United 1\u20131 Dundee|last=Winton|first=Richard|date=27 December 2019|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== January ===\nDespite having a great opportunity to gain further ground in the league in a home game against 2nd-placed [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness CT]], Dundee once again capitulated in a big game, losing 0\u20132 in a poor performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50931092|title=Dundee 0\u20132 Inverness CT|last=Smith|first=Tyrone|date=4 January 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> After their game against Ayr United was called off due to a waterlogged pitch, Dundee played their next game against [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] in the [[Scottish Cup]]. The Dark Blues yet again fell at the first hurdle in the cup and were soundly beaten by their [[Scottish Premiership|Premiership]] counterparts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51073310|title=Dundee vs Motherwell|last=Southwick|first=Andrew|date=18 January 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 January 2020}}</ref> The following week only continued the dismal play, as Dundee were completely dominated once again and failed to score for the third consecutive game in a 2\u20130 loss to Dunfermline that would have been far worse if not from some good saves by keeper [[Jack Hamilton (footballer, born 1994)|Jack Hamilton]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51144744|title=Dunfermline 2\u20130 Dundee|last=|first=|date=24 January 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== February ===\nAfter bringing in new faces in January, Dundee headed to [[Cappielow]] to face Morton. Despite taking an early lead and Morton going down to 10 men, Dundee again couldn't capitalise and could only take home a point, that along with other results dropped them down to 6th place. Dundee finally found some positive form the following week, with a comfortable 2\u20130 win at home against bottom side Partick Thistle, with [[Kane Hemmings]] scoring a brace.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51337147|title=Dundee 2\u20130 Partick Thistle|last=Crawford|first=Kenny|date=8 February 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref> Dundee were able to continue their positive swing in momentum with their first win at [[Palmerston Park]] in just over 6 years and a second consecutive clean sheet, with [[Jordon Forster]]'s strike providing Dundee the win and pulling them equal on points with 2nd-placed [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness CT]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51512645|title=Queen of the South 0\u20131 Dundee|last=|first=|date=22 February 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 February 2020}}</ref> The weather however proved too big of a match-up the following week for Dens, leading to Dundee's game with [[Arbroath F.C.|Arbroath]] to be postponed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dundeefc.co.uk/news/match-off/|title=Match off|last=|first=|date=29 February 2020|website=Dundee FC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\nDespite another impressive performance at home to Alloa which saw Dundee's third consecutive clean sheet, missed chances led to a goalless draw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51623928|title=Dundee 0\u20130 Alloa|last=Crawford|first=Kenny|date=3 March 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Dundee would extend their run to four straight clean sheets with help from a [[Conor Hazard]] penalty save, but yet again would not find the net themselves in another 0\u20130 draw away to [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51685534|title=Ayr United 0\u20130 Dundee|last=Crawford|first=Kenny|date=7 March 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> In the reverse fixture 3 days later, the Dark Blues made their chances count, combining a fifth straight clean sheet with 2 goals to again best their play-off rivals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50990656|title=Dundee 2\u20130 Ayr United|last=|first=|date=10 March 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Season suspension due to COVID-19 and voting controversy ====\nUnfortunately, Dundee's season and Scottish football's season as a whole were brought to a screeching halt on 13 March, when it was announced by the [[Scottish Professional Football League|SPFL]] that due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global coronavirus pandemic]], all future games for the season would be postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spfl.co.uk/news/coronavirus-joint-response-group-update-46618|title=Coronavirus - Joint Response Group Update|last=|first=|date=13 March 2020|website=SPFL|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The initial suspension for all Scottish football was to last until 30 April, until a further update on 9 April postponed all games until 10 June at the earliest.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52236228|title=Scottish football season suspended until 10 June|last=|first=|date=9 April 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> On 8 April the SPFL proposed a vote to end the [[2019\u201320 Scottish Professional Football League|2019\u201320 SPFL]] season (excluding the [[2019\u201320 Scottish Premiership|Scottish Premiership]] due to complications with [[UEFA]]), with all 42 SPFL member clubs voting on behalf of their current league.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spfl.co.uk/news/spfl-clubs-to-vote-on-curtailment-of-ladbrokes-s|title=SPFL clubs to vote on curtailment of Ladbrokes SPFL season 2019/20|last=|first=|date=8 April 2020|website=SPFL.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe vote was mired in controversy however, as it was revealed that one Championship club's vote, later discovered to be Dundee's, was one of only a few not received by the SPFL's requested deadline on 10 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52249263|title=SPFL vote rests on one Championship club with 28-day deadline|last=|first=|date=10 April 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> The SPFL released the received votes at 17:00, indicating that one more vote from a Championship club either for or against the proposal would decide the result, incidentally making Dundee's vote the deciding one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/dundee-confirm-spfl-resolution-stance-21849097|title=Dundee confirm SPFL resolution stance as Dens Park club decline to vote on season-ending measures and leave Scottish football in limbo|last=Jackson|first=Keith|date=10 April 2020|website=Daily Record|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Despite initial outcry regarding meeting the requested deadline, league rules indicated Dundee had 28 days to give their vote. Prior to the vote, Dundee were expected to vote against the proposal, and earlier on the day of the vote had released a statement that, while not directly stating what they intended to vote, indicated displeasure with the proposal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dundeefc.co.uk/news/club-statement-24/|title=Club Statement|last=|first=|date=10 April 2020|website=Dundee FC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe day following the vote, [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness CT]] chief executive and former Dundee CEO Scot Gardiner claimed that Dundee, Inverness and [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] had all been in agreement prior to the vote that all three clubs would all go against the proposal. Gardiner said all three clubs circulated their votes, and that Dundee supposedly sent their vote in before the 17:00 deadline on 10 April, and shared an image of a filled in voting slip signed by Dundee's Managing Director, John Nelms. When news spread that Dundee's vote had not yet been received by the SPFL, Dundee's club secretary Eric Drysdale informed the others that he had been instructed not to resubmit Dundee's vote, as it was now the casting vote and therefore held more power.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11781/11972038/spfl-resolution-inverness-chief-executive-scot-gardiner-says-dundee-claim-they-submitted-vote|title=SPFL Resolution: Inverness chief executive Scot Gardiner says Dundee claim they submitted vote|last=|first=|date=11 April 2020|website=Sky Sports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52256506|title=Inverness CT chief reveals Dundee messages in SPFL vote controversy|last=|first=|date=11 April 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> The SPFL meanwhile claimed that it had not yet received a vote from Dundee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52253331|title=Dundee were to vote against SPFL plans but league says nothing received|last=Idessane|first=Kheredine|date=11 April 2020|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> After a few days of uncertainty regarding the club's intentions, Dundee released a statement on 15 April which made clear their request for serious consideration for league reconstruction was required in order for the club to agree to the proposal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dundeefc.co.uk/news/club-statement-26/|title=Club Statement|last=|first=|date=15 April 2020|website=Dundee FC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Later that day, the SPFL announced that the proposal had officially been accepted, meaning that Dundee had voted in its favour. Their statement also included a committment to consult on potential league reconstruction via an expanded Premiership.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Competitions==\n{{legend2|#ccffcc|Win|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}} {{legend2|#ffffcc|Draw|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}} {{legend2|#ffcccc|Loss|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}} {{legend2|#cccccc|Postponed|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n''All times are in British Summer Time (BST).''\n\n===Pre-season and friendlies===\n{{Football box collapsible|id=|date=29 June 2019|time=13:00|round=[[Friendly match|Friendly]]|score=1\u20132|report=https://dundeefc.co.uk/match/brechin-pre-season/|team1=[[Brechin City F.C.|Brechin City]]|goals1=Ngoy {{goal|58}}|team2=Dundee|goals2=[[Declan McDaid|McDaid]] {{goal|42}} <br> Cameron {{goal|67}}|stadium=[[Glebe Park, Brechin|Glebe Park]], [[Brechin]]|location=|attendance=1,025|referee=Graham Beaton|result=W}}{{Football box collapsible|id=|date=2 July 2019|time=17:30|round=[[Friendly match|Friendly]]|score=0\u20130|report=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/sport/football/dundee-fc/927128/dundee-0-nottingham-forest-0-dark-blues-can-take-plenty-of-encouragement-from-spanish-draw-against-englishmen/|team1=Dundee|goals1=|team2=[[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]|goals2=|stadium=Pinatar Arena, [[San Pedro del Pinatar, Spain|San Pedro del Pinatar]]|location=|attendance=|referee=|result=D}}{{Football box collapsible|id=|date=5 July 2019|time=11:00|round=[[Friendly match|Friendly]]|score=2\u20131|report=|team1=[[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]]|goals1=[[Olufela Olomola|Olomola]] {{goal|11}} <br> [[Matty Lund|Lund]] {{goal|31}}|team2=Dundee|goals2=[[Paul McGowan (footballer)|McGowan]] {{goal|13}}|stadium=[[La Manga Club Football Stadium]], [[Spain]]|location=|attendance=[[Behind closed doors (sport)|Behind closed doors]]|result=L}}{{Football box collapsible|id=|date=9 July 2019|time=19:45|round=[[Friendly match|Friendly]]|score=1\u20130|report=https://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/fp/dundee-1-0-blackpool-dee-finish-pre-season-with-victory-over-tangerines/|team1=Dundee|goals1=[[Andrew Nelson (footballer)|Nelson]] {{goal|41}}|team2=[[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]|goals2=|stadium=[[Dens Park]], [[Dundee]]|location=|attendance=2,405|referee=|result=W}}\n\n===Scottish Championship===\n{{Main|2019\u201320 Scotti